123
00:09:42,820 --> 00:09:43,969
With his wife's help.

124
00:09:44,180 --> 00:09:45,772
Was he ranting?

125
00:09:46,580 --> 00:09:49,333
He was counting rabbits
on the ceiling.

126
00:09:49,860 --> 00:09:53,455
When he's like that
he sees animals everywhere.

127
00:09:53,660 --> 00:09:55,298
Not to mention

128
00:09:55,820 --> 00:09:59,495
the worms he keeps stabbing at
with that gold toothpick.

129
00:09:59,700 --> 00:10:01,338
He tried it on you?

130
00:10:02,700 --> 00:10:03,894
You write:

131
00:10:04,100 --> 00:10:07,217
I, the undersigned,
Elizabeth Etamble...

132
00:10:07,420 --> 00:10:08,455
<i>She wrote Betty.</i>

133
00:10:08,660 --> 00:10:10,332
Ah, no. Not Betty!

134
00:10:10,700 --> 00:10:11,894
Elizabeth!

135
00:10:20,660 --> 00:10:23,458
I, the undersigned,
Elizabeth Etamble...

136
00:10:25,340 --> 00:10:26,978
née Fayet,

137
00:10:27,940 --> 00:10:30,215
28 years old, no profession,

138
00:10:31,860 --> 00:10:35,409
residing at 6 Ave Ruysdaël, Paris,

139
00:10:37,180 --> 00:10:39,614
do hereby state

140
00:10:41,300 --> 00:10:43,291
that I accept without reservation

141
00:10:45,340 --> 00:10:47,808
the following conditions...

142
00:10:48,540 --> 00:10:49,973
I sold them.

143
00:10:50,180 --> 00:10:51,818
Sold what, my dear?

144
00:10:58,100 --> 00:11:00,694
I gotta get drunk. Excuse me.

145
00:11:00,900 --> 00:11:02,174
Of course.

146
00:11:07,580 --> 00:11:09,332
Do you live around here?

147
00:11:09,940 --> 00:11:10,736
Paris?

148
00:11:10,940 --> 00:11:12,817
I don't live anywhere!

149
00:11:14,420 --> 00:11:16,138
Would you like a small one?

150
00:11:18,820 --> 00:11:22,529
Your yank admirer
came over with NATO

151
00:11:22,740 --> 00:11:24,458
when he was about 20.

152
00:11:25,260 --> 00:11:28,696
Now that he's retired,
he's settled here.

153
00:11:28,980 --> 00:11:32,177
He comes in nearly every night
in his old uniform.

154
00:11:32,380 --> 00:11:36,976
I wrote just as they wanted,
I wrote Elizabeth, not Betty.

155
00:11:37,180 --> 00:11:39,091
And I took the check.

156
00:11:41,460 --> 00:11:42,859
And I walked out.

157
00:11:44,900 --> 00:11:48,051
You don't give a shit!
You don't give a shit!

158
00:11:53,900 --> 00:11:55,049
Mario.

159
00:12:10,820 --> 00:12:12,856
- Do you have any gauze?
- I think so.

160
00:12:13,060 --> 00:12:14,573
In the drawer.

161
00:12:20,460 --> 00:12:21,688
I'll take her home.

162
00:12:21,900 --> 00:12:22,810
You?

163
00:12:23,020 --> 00:12:24,612
- Sure, why not?
- To the Trianon?

164
00:12:26,980 --> 00:12:28,857
Couldn't she use a doctor?

165
00:12:29,260 --> 00:12:30,534
What for?

166
00:12:31,100 --> 00:12:32,738
Put her in my car.

167
00:13:00,740 --> 00:13:01,968
Be careful.

168
00:13:17,220 --> 00:13:21,213
Joseph! My friend's ill.
Is the room next to mine free?

169
00:13:21,420 --> 00:13:22,773
Of course, Madame.

170
00:14:36,740 --> 00:14:37,934
Did I wake you?

171
00:14:38,500 --> 00:14:39,694
I don't know.

172
00:14:41,620 --> 00:14:43,770
I wondered if you needed anything.

173
00:14:44,740 --> 00:14:45,695
How do you feel?

174
00:14:46,220 --> 00:14:48,017
Fine, fine.

175
00:14:48,780 --> 00:14:50,975
Even my headache's gone.

176
00:14:51,940 --> 00:14:53,214
I think I'm hungry.

177
00:14:55,700 --> 00:14:57,895
What would you like?

178
00:14:58,540 --> 00:15:00,292
Ham and eggs.

179
00:15:03,220 --> 00:15:04,130
Have you eaten?

180
00:15:04,700 --> 00:15:06,213
Yes, ages ago.

181
00:15:06,700 --> 00:15:07,769
Is it late?

182
00:15:08,580 --> 00:15:10,013
It's 4 o'clock.

183
00:15:10,660 --> 00:15:12,378
Do you like your eggs well done?

184
00:15:14,100 --> 00:15:15,135
Tea or coffee?

185
00:15:15,340 --> 00:15:16,409
Black coffee.

186
00:15:16,860 --> 00:15:21,058
Henry! I'd like some ham and eggs,
well done, and black coffee.

187
00:15:21,260 --> 00:15:23,899
Good coffee,
not this morning's dishwater.

188
00:15:24,140 --> 00:15:25,095
Thank you.

189
00:15:26,940 --> 00:15:28,373
Shall I open the curtains?

190
00:15:36,860 --> 00:15:38,976
Did you give me a shot?
I feel...

191
00:15:39,180 --> 00:15:41,250
Yes, but don't worry.

192
00:15:41,460 --> 00:15:44,179
I was a nurse for 25 years.

193
00:15:44,500 --> 00:15:46,013
My husband was a doctor.

194
00:15:46,220 --> 00:15:47,892
And I washed you,

195
00:15:48,420 --> 00:15:49,933
because you threw up.

196
00:15:51,780 --> 00:15:55,216
How about a nice hot bath
before breakfast?

197
00:15:55,500 --> 00:15:58,856
Don't get up. I'll draw your bath.

198
00:16:13,500 --> 00:16:14,728
It's not too hot?

199
00:16:14,940 --> 00:16:16,339
It's just right.

200
00:16:17,620 --> 00:16:19,451
Do you feel dizzy?

201
00:16:19,660 --> 00:16:21,218
Just a little.

202
00:16:21,940 --> 00:16:23,612
I'm ashamed I've bothered you so.

203
00:16:24,540 --> 00:16:25,859
Not at all.

204
00:16:27,660 --> 00:16:29,139
I've seen worse.

205
00:16:32,580 --> 00:16:35,048
Don't fall asleep in the water.

206
00:16:35,620 --> 00:16:36,257
I won't.

207
00:16:36,460 --> 00:16:39,691
I've been here for 3 years.
It's a bit like home.

208
00:16:43,180 --> 00:16:47,776
I sent your clothes out to clean.
The maid should bring them up.

209
00:16:56,660 --> 00:16:58,537
Just leave it here please.

210
00:17:03,380 --> 00:17:05,894
Wait. I've found you some slippers.

211
00:17:13,580 --> 00:17:14,808
They're a bit big.

212
00:17:15,340 --> 00:17:15,977
It's okay.

213
00:17:17,940 --> 00:17:19,737
I wish I knew your name.

214
00:17:20,300 --> 00:17:21,813
It's Laure.

215
00:17:22,100 --> 00:17:23,419
Laure Levaucher.

216
00:17:24,060 --> 00:17:26,620
My husband taught medecine in Lyon.

217
00:17:27,060 --> 00:17:28,573
I lost him 4 years ago.

218
00:17:31,100 --> 00:17:32,579
Aren't you eating?

219
00:17:33,700 --> 00:17:35,656
- I'm not hungry.
- Yes, you are.

220
00:17:36,140 --> 00:17:37,459
You have to eat.

221
00:17:37,700 --> 00:17:39,816
I couldn't stand living alone.

222
00:17:40,700 --> 00:17:44,170
I came here for 2 or 3 weeks' rest

223
00:17:44,460 --> 00:17:46,018
and I'm still here.

224
00:17:49,500 --> 00:17:50,569
My name's Betty.

225
00:17:51,180 --> 00:17:52,533
Bon appetit, Betty.

226
00:18:00,780 --> 00:18:02,577
I was pretty drunk, wasn't I?

227
00:18:02,780 --> 00:18:04,133
Above all, sick.

228
00:18:04,340 --> 00:18:06,251
No, I was dead drunk.

229
00:18:06,860 --> 00:18:07,815
Did I behave badly?

230
00:18:08,340 --> 00:18:12,128
Oh, my poor child!
Obviously you don't know The Hole.

231
00:18:12,860 --> 00:18:14,452
Aren't you eating?

232
00:18:14,820 --> 00:18:16,299
I can't swallow.

233
00:18:17,580 --> 00:18:20,413
Maybe you'd like to be left alone.

234
00:18:22,100 --> 00:18:24,091
Do you want to phone, write...

235
00:18:24,300 --> 00:18:25,858
No, no.

236
00:18:27,220 --> 00:18:29,814
Is there anything
you need picked up?

237
00:18:33,100 --> 00:18:33,896
I'll leave you.

238
00:18:34,100 --> 00:18:36,250
No, oh no.

239
00:18:36,940 --> 00:18:38,168
Are you all right?

240
00:18:38,380 --> 00:18:39,699
Not very.

241
00:18:40,860 --> 00:18:42,373
Do you feel nauseous?

242
00:18:43,500 --> 00:18:45,172
Do you want a drink?

243
00:18:46,740 --> 00:18:48,219
For me, that's all that works.

244
00:18:56,740 --> 00:19:00,176
That's better.
I didn't think I'd make it in time.

245
00:19:00,740 --> 00:19:02,298
Do you know where we are?

246
00:19:02,500 --> 00:19:05,776
Sure, come on.
The Trianon in Versailles.

247
00:19:06,660 --> 00:19:09,379
How about staying
for a few days' rest?

248
00:19:09,580 --> 00:19:10,729
I don't know.

249
00:19:11,500 --> 00:19:13,013
I don't feel like anything.

250
00:19:18,100 --> 00:19:19,453
Listen, Betty...

251
00:19:21,180 --> 00:19:23,330
I call you Betty,
you call me Laure.

252
00:19:23,540 --> 00:19:24,655
Okay.

253
00:19:27,620 --> 00:19:30,339
You seemed a bit lost last night.

254
00:19:31,580 --> 00:19:33,491
As if you had no place to sleep.

255
00:19:36,580 --> 00:19:38,775
Would you like
to hear my life story?

256
00:19:42,140 --> 00:19:45,416
For 28 years
I was a happy middle-class wife.

257
00:19:47,300 --> 00:19:52,328
My husband and home in Lyon
were my whole world to me.

258
00:19:53,820 --> 00:19:57,096
If I'd had children,
obviously I wouldn't be here.

259
00:19:58,540 --> 00:20:01,134
I have no more reason to live,
you see.

260
00:20:02,380 --> 00:20:04,177
I'm sure you understand.

261
00:20:06,700 --> 00:20:10,488
Before I came here,
I started drinking heavily.

262
00:20:12,500 --> 00:20:15,094
Getting away saved my life.

263
00:20:16,340 --> 00:20:19,412
What happens to me, what I do now

264
00:20:20,500 --> 00:20:22,252
no longer means anything.

265
00:20:31,540 --> 00:20:34,498
People come to visit the park,

266
00:20:34,700 --> 00:20:37,772
tourists come and go
through the hotel.

267
00:20:39,820 --> 00:20:43,017
I'm sure they think
I'm part of the staff.

268
00:20:45,380 --> 00:20:49,373
I had you put next door,
in case you needed any help.

269
00:20:49,580 --> 00:20:50,808
And I did.

270
00:20:51,020 --> 00:20:56,014
Now you can do as you like,
you can leave... or you can stay

271
00:20:56,220 --> 00:20:58,176
another day or two...

272
00:20:58,620 --> 00:20:59,575
Or change rooms...

273
00:20:59,780 --> 00:21:01,099
No, no.

274
00:21:05,860 --> 00:21:08,693
Well, tonight I'll be at The Hole.
I go every night.

275
00:21:11,460 --> 00:21:12,779
Was it your first time?

276
00:21:12,980 --> 00:21:13,856
Yes.

277
00:21:14,300 --> 00:21:15,619
Didn't you notice anything?

278
00:21:15,820 --> 00:21:18,254
In my condition... you know...

279
00:21:19,060 --> 00:21:22,018
Mario says his clients
are all twisted.

280
00:21:23,020 --> 00:21:25,659
Shall I tell you
about Mario and The Hole?

281
00:21:26,020 --> 00:21:26,532
Sure.

282
00:21:27,180 --> 00:21:28,090
Want another?

283
00:21:28,500 --> 00:21:29,649
Will it hurt me?

284
00:21:30,300 --> 00:21:31,653
It shouldn't.

285
00:21:32,420 --> 00:21:32,932
Fine.

286
00:21:33,660 --> 00:21:35,855
Mario likes to play the tough guy.

287
00:21:37,780 --> 00:21:40,533
Most clients think he was in prison.

288
00:21:41,260 --> 00:21:42,773
It excites the ladies.

289
00:21:43,860 --> 00:21:46,658
In fact, he used to be a bartender.

290
00:21:47,540 --> 00:21:50,134
And then he drove a cab in Toulon.

291
00:21:50,780 --> 00:21:54,090
But he claims he was a sailor.

292
00:21:54,620 --> 00:21:59,774
Anyway, one of his fares
was a rich South American lady.

293
00:22:00,180 --> 00:22:03,775
Her husband had just
died of a stroke,

294
00:22:04,540 --> 00:22:07,054
coming out of a Monte Carlo casino.

295
00:22:08,620 --> 00:22:11,692
He owned a cocoa plantation
in Colombia.

296
00:22:13,020 --> 00:22:15,773
Mario says she was...
absolutely twisted.

297
00:22:16,700 --> 00:22:18,497
In any case he became

298
00:22:19,220 --> 00:22:22,496
her chauffeur, factotum,
and certainly everything else.

299
00:22:23,820 --> 00:22:24,730
Am I boring you?

300
00:22:25,100 --> 00:22:27,011
On the contrary...

301
00:22:30,900 --> 00:22:35,655
I'm not sure about the rest.
Now it's a mix of fact and fiction.

302
00:22:37,380 --> 00:22:41,851
The woman was named Maria Orutti,

303
00:22:42,980 --> 00:22:45,619
from one of
the country's oldest families.

304
00:22:46,980 --> 00:22:50,609
After the husband died,
they begged her to return.

305
00:22:50,820 --> 00:22:55,814
They harrassed her with telegrams,
threatening to cut off the money.

306
00:22:56,020 --> 00:22:59,695
It made her crazy.
She'd say: "They hate me."

307
00:22:59,900 --> 00:23:04,416
<i>"It's to keel me,
to put me in an asylum</i>

308
00:23:04,620 --> 00:23:06,451
<i>"that they want me home."</i>

309
00:23:07,220 --> 00:23:11,099
<i>"Come with me. You are strong.
You will protect me."</i>

310
00:23:12,300 --> 00:23:15,417
<i>So they sailed back together.</i>

311
00:23:15,620 --> 00:23:18,180
<i>But Mario never had a chance.</i>

312
00:23:18,540 --> 00:23:23,216
<i>The family was waiting
with the police to take her away...</i>

313
00:23:27,020 --> 00:23:28,738
And how go the studies?

314
00:23:28,940 --> 00:23:30,214
All right.

315
00:23:30,420 --> 00:23:33,617
<i>So Mario was stranded
in a strange port, flat broke.</i>

316
00:23:33,940 --> 00:23:38,297
<i>He claims he had dozens of jobs,
not all so legal, it seems.</i>

317
00:23:38,500 --> 00:23:40,377
Do you know Lyon, Elizabeth?

318
00:23:41,100 --> 00:23:42,533
No, not at all.

319
00:23:43,180 --> 00:23:44,249
<i>But I think</i>

320
00:23:44,460 --> 00:23:46,610
<i>the family paid him to disappear.</i>

321
00:23:47,580 --> 00:23:50,458
<i>He roamed around
Venezuela and Panama.</i>

322
00:23:50,660 --> 00:23:55,415
<i>When he got back, he bought The Hole.
God knows how he managed,</i>

323
00:23:56,300 --> 00:23:59,053
<i>but he built up
a solid little clientele.</i>

324
00:23:59,260 --> 00:24:01,490
<i>People you never thought existed.</i>

325
00:24:01,700 --> 00:24:03,338
<i>All twisted, like he says.</i>

326
00:24:03,980 --> 00:24:05,538
People like me.

327
00:24:19,420 --> 00:24:22,253
Can I have some luggage picked up?

328
00:24:22,460 --> 00:24:26,294
Of course, Madame. Just leave us
instructions with the address.

329
00:24:26,500 --> 00:24:28,218
Charles, see to Madame.

330
00:24:29,500 --> 00:24:34,528
There'll be a few bags
and maybe a trunk.

331
00:24:35,700 --> 00:24:37,930
6 Ave Ruysdaël.

332
00:24:38,220 --> 00:24:39,539
Etamble? Like the General?

333
00:24:39,740 --> 00:24:41,173
I'm his daughter-in-law.

334
00:24:41,620 --> 00:24:44,453
Do you know how many pieces
there will be?

335
00:24:44,660 --> 00:24:45,490
No.

336
00:24:46,180 --> 00:24:47,898
Will one car be enough?

337
00:24:48,100 --> 00:24:49,658
Yes, of course.

338
00:24:49,860 --> 00:24:53,648
If you wrote a note,
that might help avoid problems.

339
00:24:57,740 --> 00:25:00,095
Will this evening be a good time?

340
00:25:01,260 --> 00:25:03,057
Will someone be there?

341
00:25:04,620 --> 00:25:09,410
<i>Please give my things
to the bearer - Thanks.</i>

342
00:25:09,620 --> 00:25:10,973
There's always someone.

343
00:25:17,140 --> 00:25:19,529
Whenever there's a storm,
I lose 2 or 3.

344
00:25:19,740 --> 00:25:21,253
Enough for a few days, eh?

345
00:25:21,460 --> 00:25:23,337
How d'you know?

346
00:25:29,580 --> 00:25:30,535
Well, Betty...

347
00:25:30,900 --> 00:25:32,413
How's the lasagna?

348
00:25:32,620 --> 00:25:33,769
It's excellent.

349
00:25:33,980 --> 00:25:35,971
Beats the shitty cassoulet?

350
00:25:36,180 --> 00:25:37,772
The cassoulet's good.

351
00:25:40,380 --> 00:25:41,733
Not so bad here, huh?

352
00:25:42,140 --> 00:25:45,257
I feel like an old customer already.

353
00:25:45,580 --> 00:25:46,854
Nice to say that.

354
00:25:47,300 --> 00:25:50,212
Looks like our gang
isn't coming out tonight.

355
00:25:51,180 --> 00:25:53,057
They're afraid to get wet.

356
00:25:53,260 --> 00:25:54,898
It's a bit early.

357
00:26:02,300 --> 00:26:03,733
So, how's the stomach?

358
00:26:03,940 --> 00:26:05,498
For the moment, okay.

359
00:26:06,020 --> 00:26:09,774
See the guy over there,
the Kojak lookalike?

360
00:26:09,980 --> 00:26:11,698
He's an English lord.

361
00:26:11,900 --> 00:26:12,935
His name's John.

362
00:26:13,460 --> 00:26:17,009
He'll sit there for hours
without a word.

363
00:26:17,700 --> 00:26:21,852
He knows when it's time to go,
down to the second.

364
00:26:22,300 --> 00:26:25,736
He'll stand up straight as a rod.

365
00:26:25,940 --> 00:26:27,658
And the girl will follow him.

366
00:26:28,260 --> 00:26:29,693
They change every week.

367
00:26:30,900 --> 00:26:33,175
And you'll never guess...

368
00:26:33,660 --> 00:26:36,220
You'll never guess what I did today.

369
00:26:36,420 --> 00:26:38,570
No, Mother, what did you do?

370
00:26:38,780 --> 00:26:40,133
Did you see a movie?

371
00:26:40,380 --> 00:26:41,972
How did you guess?

372
00:26:42,500 --> 00:26:44,138
I just said it like that.

373
00:26:45,140 --> 00:26:46,778
What did you see?

374
00:26:47,420 --> 00:26:51,333
Something about an abortionist.
I didn't like it in the least.

375
00:26:53,620 --> 00:26:56,259
Aren't you watching, Elizabeth?

376
00:26:56,620 --> 00:26:58,576
No, thank you, Mother.

377
00:27:02,620 --> 00:27:05,054
Is the television too loud, Guy?

378
00:27:05,260 --> 00:27:09,048
Not at all, Mother.
I can always work in my study.

379
00:27:09,260 --> 00:27:12,013
Oh my dear,
I like having you around me.

380
00:27:16,100 --> 00:27:18,773
Are Frederic and Odile
coming down today?

381
00:27:20,420 --> 00:27:24,572
They won't be long. I believe
they're even going out tonight.

382
00:27:24,820 --> 00:27:26,014
Where are they going?

383
00:27:26,220 --> 00:27:27,699
You can ask them.

384
00:27:32,540 --> 00:27:35,338
You ate nicely.
And now we go to bed.

385
00:27:37,500 --> 00:27:39,252
Time to go beddy-bye.

386
00:27:41,100 --> 00:27:43,330
And you too.

387
00:27:49,060 --> 00:27:53,497
After they're asleep an hour,
I'll take my night off, as you said.

388
00:28:11,820 --> 00:28:14,539
Charlotte wants to stay
with us 5 minutes.

389
00:28:15,580 --> 00:28:18,174
I advise you not to give in,
Elizabeth.

390
00:28:18,660 --> 00:28:22,335
My husband always said
to earn a child's respect, never

391
00:28:22,540 --> 00:28:23,450
give in to them.

392
00:28:23,660 --> 00:28:26,652
Well, well, well.
What's all this?

393
00:28:28,020 --> 00:28:29,453
It's out of the question.

394
00:28:30,460 --> 00:28:32,928
Off to bed like a good girl.

395
00:28:33,660 --> 00:28:38,256
Daddy has work to do. Off you go!

396
00:28:40,900 --> 00:28:41,855
Say goodnight to Grandmother.

397
00:28:42,060 --> 00:28:44,415
Good night, my dear. Sweet dreams.

398
00:28:46,500 --> 00:28:47,569
Off you go!

399
00:28:50,580 --> 00:28:53,731
We can't stay.
We have a reception at the ministry.

400
00:28:53,940 --> 00:28:55,293
You don't say!

401
00:28:55,500 --> 00:28:58,014
How lucky!
You'll be terribly amused.

402
00:28:58,220 --> 00:29:00,290
It's unspeakably dreary.

403
00:29:01,340 --> 00:29:03,695
But we can't avoid it.

404
00:29:04,340 --> 00:29:06,854
- But have a quick porto first.
- I'll get it.

405
00:29:07,060 --> 00:29:10,496
Just a drop.
We can't totter into the Ministry.

406
00:29:10,700 --> 00:29:12,019
What's the bash for?

407
00:29:12,220 --> 00:29:16,008
Some bash! The Minister
of Defense of Burkina Faso.

408
00:29:16,220 --> 00:29:17,494
<i>Oh, Negroes.</i>

409
00:29:18,100 --> 00:29:19,533
Porto, or something else?

410
00:29:29,180 --> 00:29:31,978
Thanks, my dear. Will you serve?

411
00:29:36,820 --> 00:29:38,492
Not having any, Elizabeth?

412
00:29:38,700 --> 00:29:40,418
No, I'm not.

413
00:29:41,740 --> 00:29:43,617
Happy with the nurse?

414
00:29:43,820 --> 00:29:44,730
Yes.

415
00:29:45,300 --> 00:29:48,258
She's so perfect,
we almost feel like intruders.

416
00:29:48,940 --> 00:29:53,058
That's the problem:
Either they're possessive or inept.

417
00:29:53,260 --> 00:29:54,010
Frédéric, remember...

418
00:29:54,220 --> 00:29:57,018
...Antoine's German nurse?
- Don't mention her.

419
00:29:57,220 --> 00:30:00,371
A pain in the ass,
if you'll excuse me.

420
00:30:00,580 --> 00:30:02,855
I had to apply for visiting rights.

421
00:30:03,220 --> 00:30:04,130
You're exaggerating.

422
00:30:04,620 --> 00:30:06,099
Not at all.

423
00:30:06,380 --> 00:30:10,373
Remember, Guy?
Before you were with us, Betty.

424
00:30:10,580 --> 00:30:14,573
What was her name, Frédéric?

425
00:30:15,020 --> 00:30:16,089
Not Big Bertha?

426
00:30:17,420 --> 00:30:18,694
You're always joking!

427
00:30:19,220 --> 00:30:20,972
Frédéric! What was her name?

428
00:30:21,580 --> 00:30:23,252
<i>I think it was Bertha.</i>

429
00:30:23,460 --> 00:30:24,893
Why, no!

430
00:30:25,100 --> 00:30:28,410
Mother, remember the German nurse?

431
00:30:28,980 --> 00:30:30,698
What was her name?

432
00:30:34,260 --> 00:30:35,329
Mom?

433
00:30:36,020 --> 00:30:37,419
Is she asleep?

434
00:30:43,340 --> 00:30:44,534
My God!

435
00:30:45,060 --> 00:30:46,129
What is it?

436
00:30:47,220 --> 00:30:48,858
I don't know. She looks dead.

437
00:30:49,260 --> 00:30:53,731
She watched him laid out on the bed

438
00:30:54,180 --> 00:30:56,057
for more than an hour.

439
00:30:56,260 --> 00:30:59,252
Finally she realized he was asleep,

440
00:30:59,460 --> 00:31:01,655
an empty glass in his hand.

441
00:31:02,620 --> 00:31:04,690
Really twisted.

442
00:31:06,180 --> 00:31:07,932
What are you thinking about?

443
00:31:08,900 --> 00:31:10,618
My mother-in-law.

444
00:31:11,140 --> 00:31:12,971
Oh, but I know her.

445
00:31:13,180 --> 00:31:16,217
We lived on the same street in Lyon.

446
00:31:16,420 --> 00:31:18,888
- Strange, I had a feeling.
- Oh, really?

447
00:31:19,100 --> 00:31:20,533
She had a heart attack, you know?

448
00:31:20,740 --> 00:31:22,253
My god! When was that?

449
00:31:22,460 --> 00:31:24,610
It was 7 or 8 months ago.

450
00:31:25,100 --> 00:31:26,579
And how is she now?

451
00:31:26,780 --> 00:31:29,852
Oh, she's fully recovered now.

452
00:31:30,260 --> 00:31:33,889
She's been back in Paris 3...
no, 4 days.

453
00:31:34,100 --> 00:31:35,852
She's staying with us,

454
00:31:36,060 --> 00:31:38,972
I mean my husband, Guy,
the younger son.

455
00:31:40,020 --> 00:31:44,298
The one who refused an army career.
The General was livid.

456
00:31:44,500 --> 00:31:49,096
The older one, he's working
in the Defense Ministry. Frédéric.

457
00:31:49,500 --> 00:31:52,856
He lives above our place.
I mean Guy's.

458
00:31:53,060 --> 00:31:56,416
Yes, he married the Fleury girl.
Odile, no?

459
00:31:56,620 --> 00:31:58,656
I knew her sister quite well.

460
00:31:58,860 --> 00:32:01,772
A Lyon family,
vaguely related to mine.

461
00:32:02,460 --> 00:32:04,655
And your mother-in-law
is a Gomieux.

462
00:32:08,140 --> 00:32:11,576
...except... Hector,
an oculist in Broussais.

463
00:32:12,340 --> 00:32:15,059
This is like being in a Lyon salon.

464
00:32:15,820 --> 00:32:18,459
That's what we call
dead weight of Society.

465
00:32:19,260 --> 00:32:22,696
I know that the Etambles have
a country estate in Chassagne wood,

466
00:32:22,900 --> 00:32:26,973
near Chalamont,
where my brother shoots duck.

467
00:32:28,100 --> 00:32:30,853
I went there
each of our 6 married years.

468
00:32:31,220 --> 00:32:33,370
The family spent August there.

469
00:32:33,660 --> 00:32:36,174
The General, his wife,
the 2 brothers,

470
00:32:36,420 --> 00:32:38,012
their wives, the children.

471
00:32:39,020 --> 00:32:40,658
A nightmare, those summers.

472
00:32:42,060 --> 00:32:44,415
Frédéric and Guy
playing tennis all day.

473
00:32:47,980 --> 00:32:50,972
I suppose you'd like
to have lasagna.

474
00:32:51,580 --> 00:32:52,535
What else
do you have?

475
00:32:52,740 --> 00:32:53,968
Lasagna.

476
00:32:55,700 --> 00:32:57,372
We made a mistake.

477
00:32:58,300 --> 00:33:00,291
That's what I figured.

478
00:33:00,860 --> 00:33:01,975
Okay. We'll have lasagna.

479
00:33:02,180 --> 00:33:03,249
There you are!

480
00:33:06,700 --> 00:33:09,976
I have two children. Two girls.

481
00:33:10,300 --> 00:33:13,337
Charlotte is 4
and Anne-Marie 19 months.

482
00:33:13,540 --> 00:33:16,179
Starting to talk like a real person.

483
00:33:16,980 --> 00:33:18,618
Good evening Laure...

484
00:33:19,420 --> 00:33:22,298
I hope you excuse my decamping

485
00:33:22,660 --> 00:33:25,936
last night.
I believe Laure explained...

486
00:33:30,700 --> 00:33:33,294
You didn't surprise your aunt?

487
00:33:33,500 --> 00:33:38,255
Oh Daddy. Auntie was arranging
the attic. Remember the attic?

488
00:33:38,460 --> 00:33:43,215
<i>So we climbed up silently.
And then Laurence goes mooooo...</i>

489
00:33:43,420 --> 00:33:44,091
Really, Laurence.

490
00:33:44,300 --> 00:33:46,689
Like a cow had snuck into the attic.

491
00:33:46,900 --> 00:33:51,337
Auntie was so scared
she dropped a pile of books.

492
00:33:55,260 --> 00:33:56,898
It's not their fault.

493
00:33:57,100 --> 00:33:58,010
Pardon?

494
00:33:59,700 --> 00:34:02,055
Would you mind if we left?

495
00:34:02,940 --> 00:34:04,498
Don't you feel well?

496
00:34:04,700 --> 00:34:06,497
I just want to go back.

497
00:34:09,980 --> 00:34:12,016
Excuse me, Madame Etamble.

498
00:34:12,860 --> 00:34:15,579
I've put your luggage in your room.

499
00:34:15,780 --> 00:34:18,214
The driver left this for you.

500
00:34:24,340 --> 00:34:26,979
It's Elda's writing. The nurse.

501
00:34:27,260 --> 00:34:29,137
She packed my bags.

502
00:34:33,460 --> 00:34:35,690
Well, I'll leave you, as you...

503
00:34:35,940 --> 00:34:36,850
You're going back?

504
00:34:37,060 --> 00:34:38,175
No, no, but

505
00:34:38,380 --> 00:34:42,214
I imagine you want
to unpack your bags in peace.

506
00:34:42,420 --> 00:34:44,012
Do you mind staying?

507
00:34:44,220 --> 00:34:46,939
Not at all! I don't want to impose.

508
00:34:47,340 --> 00:34:50,457
I absolutely adore packing
and unpacking.

509
00:34:50,700 --> 00:34:55,216
I used to spend all day packing
for trips with my husband.

510
00:34:56,780 --> 00:34:58,498
My mink.

511
00:34:58,740 --> 00:34:59,855
<i>It's an investment.</i>

512
00:35:01,300 --> 00:35:05,373
And as you'll need it one day,

513
00:35:05,740 --> 00:35:09,972
best buy it now since it will
cost more in 2 or 3 years.

514
00:35:10,500 --> 00:35:12,775
Guy said it was an investment.

515
00:35:13,300 --> 00:35:15,018
I was afraid he'd keep it.

516
00:35:20,620 --> 00:35:22,736
I'll fix you a drink.

517
00:35:22,940 --> 00:35:25,977
I'm embarrassed. You always buy.

518
00:35:26,180 --> 00:35:28,011
I promise I'll let you

519
00:35:28,220 --> 00:35:30,575
buy the next bottle. The next two!

520
00:35:33,940 --> 00:35:35,339
My daughters.

521
00:35:37,220 --> 00:35:40,576
This one looks like you.
She has your eyes.

522
00:35:43,780 --> 00:35:47,455
Cheers! To you, and for all
you've done for me.

523
00:35:51,540 --> 00:35:53,690
But they're not my children now.

524
00:35:58,460 --> 00:36:01,418
In fact, I don't think
they ever were.

525
00:36:01,620 --> 00:36:03,975
Except when I was expecting.

526
00:36:04,260 --> 00:36:06,251
Do you believe in motherly love?

527
00:36:07,900 --> 00:36:11,973
Ah, I forgot. You don't have kids.
You couldn't know.

528
00:36:12,340 --> 00:36:17,016
Maternal love, like in books or
songs, like we're taught at school.

529
00:36:17,340 --> 00:36:19,615
I believed in it when I got married.

530
00:36:20,980 --> 00:36:22,891
One day I'd have children.

531
00:36:23,100 --> 00:36:27,013
A nice idea, part of a whole:
A home, a family.

532
00:36:27,420 --> 00:36:31,015
When I learned I was pregnant
I was confused.

533
00:36:31,220 --> 00:36:33,529
I didn't expect it so soon.

534
00:36:34,700 --> 00:36:39,251
<i>Married just 2 years, and now
everyone only spoke of the child.</i>

535
00:36:39,460 --> 00:36:41,974
<i>Even before its birth
I was the mother.</i>

536
00:36:43,420 --> 00:36:44,978
Maybe I was jealous.

537
00:36:45,660 --> 00:36:47,378
But I don't really think so.

